      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i'm working on my psych dissertation and i'm stuck on a weird result. my effect size looks pretty decent but my p-value is 0.06. can u explain why this is technically \"not significant\" even if there's a clear trend in the data? also i feel like there's just so much noise in the sample making it hard to see the actual signal.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A p-value of 0.06, even with a decent effect size, is not significant because, by the strict rules of the statistical $\\text{t}$-test or $\\text{F}$-test, you haven't quite crossed the threshold of the predetermined significance level, which is usually set at $\\alpha = 0.05$. Think of it like this: the null hypothesis is a very stubborn opponent, and your data, while showing a clear lean, hasn't delivered enough evidence to make the judge—the statistical test—declare a victory. It's a bit like trying to catch a slippery, wiggling piece of raw meat; you see the shape, but you can't quite pin it down with the net yet.\n\nThe noise you're feeling is the classic problem of sample size, or perhaps just the inherent randomness of the data, which is a real pain in the backside. It's the constant battle against the *random* things—the little flickers and jitters that make up the background static. You've got to be careful not to let the noise trick you into thinking you've found a solid nugget of gold when it's just a pile of shiny",
      "source": "target",
