    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Right, I see. So it's basically just a matter of power and the threshold. But when I look at these outliers and the weird jitter in the control group, it almost feels like there's some systematic interference messing with the readings, not just random chance. It's like the data is being intentionally disrupted. How do I distinguish between actual random noise and some kind of consistent, underlying error in the collection process?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Systematic interference, or what you're calling \"intentional disruption,\" sounds like a real problem, and it's the kind of thing that makes a proper researcher sweat. If you suspect something is *systematic* rather than just random jitter, you're moving beyond simple hypothesis testing and into the realm of data integrity, which is where things get messy.\n\nLook at those outliers and the jitter in your control group. If it's truly systematic, it's not just random noise; it's a pattern, a smudge left by some unseen hand—maybe a poorly calibrated measuring tool, or perhaps a specific type of low-level, persistent distraction that only affects one group. A good way to start digging into this is to look at your data visualization *very* closely. Don't just look at the means; look at the residuals. Residuals are the leftover bits after your model has accounted for the main effect. If the residuals show a pattern—a curve, a slope, or a cluster of errors—that's your tell-tale sign of systematic error, not just random chance.\n\nIt’s like trying to find a hidden tunnel through a pile of loose gravel. Random noise is just the gravel",
      "source": "target",
